\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 BREAKFAST WITH KIDS\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
"Do you think you're smarter than me?"\
\
Those were the words that came out my mouth to my 12 year old daughter. We were having a great breakfast together as a family. We had just started this new routine and I was excited. Excited to spend more time with my kids, excited to be able to hear their stories, and most importantly excited to speak into their lives at such a formative time. \
\
I was walking through a list of activities I wanted them to start to do to help create some more consistent routine in their lives. It was summer so they were not exactly excited to have dad at the table talking about habits but that was the conversation. \
\
In the list of activities I mentioned brushing your teeth before we eat was one of them. Emma mentioned she likes to brush her teeth after she eats. Now I could spend the next few paragraphs telling you why that isn't a good idea and you should always brush you teeth before you eat, but I'll spare you the speech. \
\
I didn't spare them the speech. I was actually excited. This was one of those moments I was looking forward to. To impart my wisdom I've acquired over the years and shape the young minds that sat before me. I spent a solid two minutes doing my best to challenge and motivate my kids to brush their teeth first. When I was finished I felt like I nailed it. \
\
Ever feel like that as a parent? Like you just molded some impressionable and they are now better for having you in their life. Well, if you're a parent then you know what comes next. Emma doesn't even look up at me, she just calmly states that she'll probably still brush her teeth afterwards.\
\
To say I was frustrated or angry is an understatement. Which led to my question I asked immediately  - "Do you think you're smarter than me?". She looked at me weird as if this was an odd question and told me 'no'. But the question was important one. I wanted her to think about why she just said what she said. How could she listen to me, know me as a loving father, know that I'm smarter than her, and still not want to do what I was asking her to do.\
\
At the core, she was doing what so many of us do when it comes to God. \
\
If we were having coffee and I asked you if you were smarter than God, most, maybe not all, would say "Of course not". You may even look at me with the same odd ball look my daughter gave. The "Why would you even ask that question" look. \
\
But, if we were to look a little deeper at your life and not just your words, it might show a very different picture. All of us, no matter who you are, have the ability to hear God's word in our lives, believe He is right, and yet still go off and want to do whatever we want to do. We can intellectually know that God is smarter and He wants the best for us, but there is something in our hearts that pushes us to go our own way, to want to have the autonomy to do whatever we want to do not matter what God has said.  \
\
Why do we do that? How can we say we trust in God, love God, want to follow God, listen to God, and believe in God...and yet after we hear or read His word go and do whatever we want?\
\
Remember those statements we talked about in the first chapter?\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li720\fi-720\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I can handle it\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I don't have a problem \
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I would never act on that thought\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}It'll be ok\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I can stop anytime I want to\
