\cf0 \
Those thoughts are what was we use as to feed the alligator.\
\
When we justify behavior or thoughts we shouldn't engage in we are feeding not just any alligator but the biggest and baddest one out there...pride.\
\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 THE PROBLEM NO ONE HAS
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 \
Why do I think it's the biggest baddest one? You may not see it yet but the church fathers did. In fact there was a pretty clear consensus for how they saw pride.\
\
Why?\
\
Because pride is considered by many of the church fathers to be the core sin that leads to all other sins. Evagrius (345-399), who created the Evil Eight list we read in the last chapter) listed hubris (pride) as the prime logismos, a chief temptation, from which all other sins arise. (1 footnote here). St. Gregory the Great (540-604) described pride as "the root of all evil...the first progeny" of sin. (2 footnote here). And St. Thomas Aquinas called pride "the first sin and the source of all other sins, and the worst sin" (3 footnote here)\
\
Essentially what they are saying is It is the catalyst for every other wrong thing you do. If you can control this one sin then the rest just sort of go away. Don't feed this alligator and the rest starve by default. It's that important.\
\
The problem is most people don't think they have a problem with pride. I rarely run into people who deep down believe they are arrogant and proud.  And the ones that do have pride many times don't see it as a problem. They'll tell you they are confident or just great. They'll tell you things like they don't need others help or they've got it. They won't tell you they are prideful with their words directly but they'll tell you all about how awesome they were in high school playing football. (You know who you are).\
\
In fact as a culture we even have a whole month set aside to celebrate how proud we are of the pride we have. \
\
But if you were to look back at some of, if not all, of your biggest regrets, you knew better. It wasn't an information issue for your head but a transformation issue of your heart. You knew what to do or what not to do and you did it anyway, only to wake up and find yourself in a place you don't want to be.\
\
This is why in Proverbs 16:18 the author tells us that God opposes the proud.\
\
That's a strong statement. Most of us would want God on our side, God to bless our work and what we're doing. Most don't want to fight with God.\
\
But most of us don't take pride serious enough or even see it in our own lives to fight against.\
\
Still don't believe pride is that big of a deal? Maybe this story will help.\
\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 WHAT'S BIG DEAL ABOUT AN APPLE?\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
I tell my church all the time that the stories in the Bible are not just THEIR stories but OUR stories. This is no more true than the original story, the first one, the beginning story in the garden with Adam and Eve.\
\
If you're not super familiar with it, here is the quick recap. God creates everything in Chapter 1 of Genesis and there is a phrase repeated over and over. After every day it says " and it was good". Day 1 was good, day 2 was good, day 3...you guessed it...good. All the way up to day 5. All of creation was 'good'. This is important because sometime I think we can think the garden was perfect but it wasn't. It was good. God created a good place for Adam and Eve to live. \
\
Something subtle happens on the sixth day though. God creates humanity and the language adds just one word. Instead of it being 'good' it reads 'very good'. I absolutely love this small addition to the text. Because from the beginning God created us and saw us not just like all of creation but as separate, as different, as beings who have inherent value not because of what we do but because of who we are. We are in God's eyes VERY GOOD.\
\
The story of God and His creation starts our serenity, not sin.\
\
This matters because I've been too many church services where the sermon is "you're just a sinner saved by grace". The pastor many times wants you to feel bad about who you are in an attempt to make you feel good about who God is. That's bad theology and needs to be rejected completely! But, I'm getting ahead of myself, we'll come back to that statement later.\
\
Until then I want you to know you were made in the image of your creator. You are not an accident. You are loved and pursued by a Holy God who sees you, your pain, your past and is pursuing you. Because while He see's you past and your pain, He also sees your future and what could be. He knows not just what is behind you but what is in front of you.  \
\
Back to the story.\
\
So chapters 1 and 2 things are good. Humanity is very good. In chapter 3 things take a turn for the worse. Whether you grew up in church or not there's a good chance you're familiar with the story. \
\
God tells Adam to do a few things, one in particular is to make sure you don't eat from the fruit of one tree. To our knowledge we don't know if God told him why, but it's pretty clear God told him what not to do. \
\
Maybe you're one of those people who is a little negative on this story. Maybe you're asking questions like why would God do that? Why put options when you are looking for obedience? I get it. I've asked those questions too. And while I don't have any great answers I've come to two conclusions:\
\
The first is that sometimes we can look at this story all wrong. One way to look at what God was withholding from Adam. Why would God create this great place to live and then put the one thing that can ruin it right in the middle of the garden? Why would he set Adam up to fail like that? But the other way to look at it is to look at what God gave Adam. Think about it. God gave Adam literally EVERYTHING but ONE THING. He could eat, go, and do anything he wanted to except for one thing. That sounds like an incredible deal. \
\
Think about it today. If God looked at you and said you can do anything you want, you can spend your time however you want, you just can't eat Oreo Blizzards (you can replace that with whatever it is that is your kryptonite but that's mine). If God was giving me literally everything I would gladly, willingly, and gleefully accept that. I wouldn't view God as negative or withholding but as good and loving.\
\
Maybe you're not there yet and that's ok...\
\
The second conclusion I've come to is that without 
\f1\b OPTIONS
\f0\b0  it is impossible to have real 
\f1\b OBEDIENCE
\f0\b0 . When I was in high school I was a pretty good kid. I never went to any parties, didn't get drunk or get high on any drugs, and up until my senior year never  went on a single date. I was a good...externally. But what if I told you all of those external ways I was 'obeying' God were more about a lack of options.  In fact I was never invited to a party. I was never once offered drugs or alcohol. And when it comes to sex...let's just say no one was offering. \
\
Honestly, I wasn't an obedient loyal child of God, I was a lonely kid with no options. I wasn't walking around pursuing holiness and purity, I just wasn't invited to the parties. I would have loved to have a girlfriend, there were just no offers. In fact, the first girl I ever dated, it didn't take long for me to compromise that purity...but again...I'm getting ahead of myself. \
\
The point is to be good you have to first have an option to be bad. To show loyalty you have to be able to show disloyalty first. To really love someone you have first have to have the ability to leave them or forsake them. God ultimately wants a relationship with you. He wants you to actually choose Him over other options, and the only way you can truly choose to follow, trust, and love God is when there are others to choose from. \
\
So we live in a world of options to choose from. Every day we get to either choose God or choose someone or something else.\
\
So Adam and Eve are in this garden and ultimately they choose to disobey God's one and only command. They ate from the tree they were suppose to.\
\
But didn't we start out talking about pride? What's that have to do with an apple?\
\
Let's read it together.\
