\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
There is so much here to look at but for right now it's just one thing. It's the conversation. It would be easy to point to their actions but as I've been saying this whole time. The alligators that get us and destroy our lives always start small. This situation is no different. It's starts small. It's starts out not as open rebellion against God but as a conversation about God. \
\
If you were to reread it again what I hope you would notice is as much what is NOT said, as what IS said. The serpent doesn't come to Eve with a challenge or call for her to sin. He doesn't tell her to forget about God. He doesn't even tell her to eat the apple. He just questions God goodness. He questions whether God is holding out on them. He knows that if he can put doubt into their minds then they will do the rest. \
\
Never once does the serpent tell them what to do, he just questions who God is. \
\
And in that moment Eve starts to question a few things. Did God really say? And if He did, why? And even if He did say that, is God holding out on me? And if He is, what am I missing out on? Ultimately the question Eve had to answered and answered wrong is this - Can I trust in the commands of God?\
\
I don't know how long she paused and stood there looking at the apple. In my mind it wasn't instantaneous. She sat there for a second. Waffling back and forth. Torn by a new dilemma. Deciding in her head. ThInking through what's the worst that could happen. Maybe even questioning whether God would really kill her. It's just an apple, what's the big deal about an apple anyway.\
\
Maybe you're still not connecting this to pride so let me help. The goal of the Serpent was to push Eve to the point where she stood in the place of God and judge whether His commands were good or not. Whether he could be trusted or not. Whether He was who He said He was or not. When she looked at the fruit as an option she started to become judge and jury over her own life. \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 I said it earlier, I'm going to say it again...This story...it's OUR story. We live out this story almost daily. Every temptation we come across, every compromise we run into, this is what happens. This is the conversation we have with ourselves.  \
\
Can i trust in the God who created me, loves, and has given me good guardrails to guide me?\
\
You probably don't out and out question the goodness of God. And you've probably never talked to a snake about some fruit on a tree (if you do there are some drugs that can help with that). But you've talked to a snake named Chad before who left you feeling guilty about a one night stand. You've talked to snake named Jennifer about the deal of a lifetime and you would be foolish to miss out on it, you just need to purchase it today before someone else gets it before you.\
\
See there are snakes all around us. And when we talk to snakes the conversations will lead us to the point where we start talking to ourselves. Not about apples but maybe about an apple phone. It just sounds a little different. \
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li720\fi-720\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I know I shouldn't think those negative thoughts about them but it's not like they can hear me (The pride of thinking God's commands are solely based on pragmatic causes and effect that you can see)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I know I shouldn't be sleeping with that person but come on...it's two consenting adults and It's not hurting anyone. (The pride of thinking what God said about sexual sin doesn't apply to your situation)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I know that God loves me and would want me to be happy so this is ok (The pride of believing God's love would never call you to sacrifice or suffer for His glory)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I know I shouldn't but no one is perfect and so it'll be ok (The pride of thinking somehow God is comparing you to others instead of Himself and the standard of His perfection)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}I don't care if it's wrong, I want it now and I was going to get it later anyway (The pride of thinking you know the future and somehow God making you wait has no spiritual or formative effect on you)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}It's not like it's life or death (The pride of thinking that God wont' kill you for openly rebelling against Him in such a disrespectful way)\
\pard\tx560\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Starting to see it? When we question WHAT God has said and WHO He has called us to become, we question God. And it is only pride, arrogance, and self-idolatry that would ever lead us to think this way.\
\
See, in the garden it really had nothing to do with the apple. It was never about the apple. It was about the choice of God command or their own person desire. It was never about the apple but about which truth they were going to lean into, God's truth that they would die or the serpents truth that they won't. Ultimately it was never about the apple but trust. In the absence of what you want, would Adam and Eve still trust in God. Would they be willing to forgo what they wanted in that moment for what God wanted for their future. \
\
Every single time we sin, we are telling God we don't trust him, we believe His words are true and good, and we are choosing something else for our lives.  Can there be anything more prideful than to look at the All-Powerful, All-Knowing, All-Loving God and say we don't care what He wants, we're going to do our own thing. I don't think so, which is why it's such a big deal. It would have been easy for Eve to justify talking to the serpent. She was just talking, she wasn't going to eat the apple. She even told the serpent she wasn't going to initially. But she fed the alligator. She fed it with some questions of God's goodness and one thing lead to another and well you know how it ends. The apple was never the issue. The apple was the symptom, the disease was the pride that lead her to believe the apple would be worth the price. \
