\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 SPIRITUAL CANCER
\f0\b0\fs28 \
\
"It's cancer."  \
\
I'm not sure there are scarier words when you're sitting in a doctor's office. In that moment your world changes whether it is about you or someone you love. No one hears those words and walks out the same. \
\
So imagine for a second after the doctor tells you about the cancer, she then says "It's just a little cancer and so not a big deal though, I wouldn't worry about. You can handle it. It's not hurt before. It's still small and manageable. It's not really hurting anyone right now."\
\
Don't worry about it? Are you kidding? It's cancer!\
\
What's your next move? What do you do with that information? \
\
Me, I'm finding a new doctor. I'm telling everyone I know to avoid that person as a doctor. \
\
Why? Because cancer is a disease that kills. It destroys. it has one goal and that is to replicate itself to the point your body quits functioning the way it is intended to. Untreated it is a death sentence. \
\
You can't convince me NOT to take ti seriously. A 'little' cancer is still cancer. \
\
My assumption is your probably like me. There are things that need to be taken seriously, especially when the stakes are so high. \
\
CS Lewis stated it perfectly when he said,"For pride is spiritual cancer: it eats up the very possibility of love, or contentment, or common sense"\
\
I think that is the perfect image of what pride is and why God takes it so seriously. I'm pretty sure you wouldn't take cancer lightly but so many of us take pride lightly. We see it as small, as this little thing that we may or may not have but it's manageable. It's the small alligator we play with most of our lives not realizing it is what is holding you back spiritually. If we would just take pride as serious as God takes it then the world would be a completely different place. If the church would just take pride seriously the world would be different.  \
\
Maybe you've never thought about it this way but you have a spiritual cancer. It's called 'sin'. It's a condition we are all born with. Every person walking this earth has sinned, is sinning, and in the future will sin. \
\
Don't believe me, if you have kids you know, you don't have to teach them to hit someone when they get mad, steal something from someone else when they want it, or scream at the top of their lungs when they don't get what they want. You have to teach them to be kind, be gentle, be generous, be loving, be all the things we value in our society as good. We come out of the womb a bundle of desires that are contrary to what is good and whole. \
\
You may not call it sin though, you call it mistakes, problems, deficiencies, unlearned behavior, etc...\
\
Honestly it doesn't matter nearly as much what you call it as what you do with it. The average person today doesn't take sin seriously. We have this cancer in our hearts that push us and prod us to act in ways that are contrary to who we know we are called to be. We shock ourselves, disappoint ourselves, and hurt what we value most. \
\
No one gets through this life unscathed and uninterrupted by sin. It disrupts so much of what we do.\
\
The problem is we don't treat sin like the spiritual cancer that it is. We treat sin like pet alligators that we can manage, play with, and they won't bite us. We are like the doctor who sees the cancer but isn't worried. It's our little pet sin, it's not hurting anyone, I can handle that addiction, I would never act on those thoughts, it hasn't hurt me yet, I'll be ok I've done this before and been fine.\
\
See the problem yet? As terrible as cancer is, and is ravaging to the body, sin is worse. And we need to start treating like the cancer in our lives that it is. \
\
It's a killer, and it's killing you more than you realize.\
\
So when someone has cancer there are a few ways to deal with it. One of the most common is to cut it out. To do surgery and remove all of the infected area so it doesn't infect the rest of the body. In fact, you would never cut most of it out. The doctor would never settle for getting 'most' of it. You stay there with the person open until you get it all. It's that important because of what's at stake. \
\
That is what we need to do here. We need to engage in some spiritual surgery. We need to open up our lives and take a deeper look and cut out any and all parts that don't line up with God's call in our lives.\
\
\

