\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
There's a passage that confused me for years. It felt extreme and I honestly wasn't sure what it meant until I spent some time meditating on it. It's found in Proverbs chapter 4 the author introduces one of the most powerful, convicting thoughts in all of scripture. In fact if you can get this next passage and apply it to your life it will radically change you overnight, it's that powerful.\
\
Here is what it says: \
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf2 23\'a0Above all else, guard your heart,\uc0\u8232 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0for everything you do flows from it.\
24\'a0Keep your mouth free of perversity;\uc0\u8232 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0keep corrupt talk far from your lips.\
25\'a0Let your eyes look straight ahead;\uc0\u8232 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0fix your gaze directly before you.\
26\'a0Give careful thought to the[c] paths for your feet\uc0\u8232 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0and be steadfast in all your ways.\
27\'a0Do not turn to the right or the left;\uc0\u8232 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0keep your foot from evil.  \
Proverbs 4\cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
A few things here. The first is the author tells us that in his estimation, the single more important thing you can do in life is to guard your heart. To ensure that what you put into your heart is only good things. Why? Because every action you do, every word you speak, every thought you have flows out of that heart. Sound familiar? This has echos of what Jesus said in the last chapter. The problem for all of us is not what is happening AROUND us but what we allow IN us.\
\
What he is saying is when we guard our hearts we guard against sin. \
\
The best part is if you keep reading he gives some very helpful specific things to watch out for. Make sure we are not laughing at corse jokes and speaking about perverse things. We need to make sure you what we are looking at is pure and is focused on where we want to be in the future. He tells us to think through our paths and not just be reactive. \
\
But then the confusing part for me. Don't turn to the left or right? That felt odd and out of place. What's wrong with left or right. I get why you shouldn't turn around. I completely understand why you shouldn't look back. But left or right? Seems controlling, seems extreme, seems like left or right wouldn't be a big deal.\
\
Then one day as I was thinking about this passage it hit me, and maybe you've already figure it out (if you have just pretend with me you haven't) \
\
If you never turn left or right, you'll never turn around. \
\
Compromise always starts with small adjustments to our path. When following God i've yet to meet the person who woke up one morning and said to themselves "I think today I'll nuke my marriage." Or the person who was doing amazing financially and thought "Today is the day I go into crippling debt to the point I can't breathe financially". Or the person who wakes up and says "I hope I walk so far from God I can't feel His presence anymore."\
\
Nope, they are small adjustment to the path they are on. Small compromises of pride that says I don't have to do things perfectly, I don't have follow God completely, I'll be ok. \
\
When we realize it becomes clear where to start. In fact every sin we engage in started with a small compromise that wasn't a sin in the way we think about sin. It wasn't bad...it just wasn't good. It was morally neutral.\
\
\
